s such as Black Lives Matter in the United States, this account attests to an ongoing struggle for Black liberation in the wake of formal racial inclusion.Rather than unified resistance, however, class struggles within the process of racial inclusion produced a fractured militancy. Revealing the complicated truth behind the celebrated "success" of South African democratization, Paret uncovers a society divided by wealth, urban geography, nationality, employment, and political views. Fractured Militancy warns of the threat that capitalism and elite class struggles present to social movements and racial justice everywhere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBlack peoplexPolitical activityzSouth Africa. 0aBlack peoplezSouth AfricaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aBlack peoplezSouth AfricaxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aBlacksxPolitical activityzSouth Africa. 0aBlackszSouth AfricaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aBlackszSouth AfricaxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aPolitical culturezSouth Africa. 0aPost-apartheid erazSouth Africa. 0aSocial classesxEconomic aspectszSouth Africa. 4aAfrican Hist & Diaspora. 4aLabor History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aProtest in South Africa, Racial capitalism in South Africa, Post apartheid South Africa, Johannesburg’s impoverished urban Black neighborhoods, Black liberation movements, black lives matter.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075182640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176181240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501761812423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501761812/original  a978-3-11-075182-6  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_S